<div id="review_1255905607" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1255905607" />
    <a title="Saz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30501922-saz"><img alt="Saz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1508455965p2/30501922.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1255905607?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Saz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Saz" href="/user/show/30501922-saz">Saz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30501922-saz?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1255905607" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10353343081663840641">I&apos;m conflicted. Fauziya&apos;s story was a compelling one, and as a woman who was, too, once a refugee, I realize how important her story is. However, I felt that it was very redundant. There were times I cried, times that I couldn&apos;t put the book down and could hardly wait to flip the page...but the bulk of this novel went by slowly...it was a bit agonizing. The book starts out with her life - her family is introduced and she takes us through her life in chronological order - up until the point where</span>
  <span id="freeText10353343081663840641" style="display:none">I'm conflicted. Fauziya's story was a compelling one, and as a woman who was, too, once a refugee, I realize how important her story is. However, I felt that it was very redundant. There were times I cried, times that I couldn't put the book down and could hardly wait to flip the page...but the bulk of this novel went by slowly...it was a bit agonizing. The book starts out with her life - her family is introduced and she takes us through her life in chronological order - up until the point where her life took a sharp downwards spiral. Then we read about her experiences as a detainee. I understand this is perhaps one of the most crucial points and messages of the story. Yet, I feel that it could have been cut down some. I feel horrible typing this out because I don't mean to downplay what she went through, but most of this book was wait, talk to lawyers, cry, get sick, repeat. Over and over and over and over and over again until the last chapter of the book. <br />It was a bit exhausting. <br />Nevertheless it was a good story, and the reason I gave it 3 stars was because the beginning and endings compensated for the what the middle of the book lacked, I think. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10353343081663840641" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


